00:00:01:556000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:00:01:556000.Dialogue: All right, I'm ready for my next question.

00:00:04:392000.Speaker: Amy
00:00:04:392000.Dialogue: In a world where rhinoceroses are domesticated pets, who wins the Second World War?

00:00:15:353000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:00:15:353000.Dialogue: Kenya rises to power on the export of rhinoceroses. A Central African power block is formed, colonizing North Africa and Europe. When war breaks out, no one can afford the luxury of a rhino. Kenya withers, Uganda triumphs.

00:00:35:039000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:00:35:039000.Dialogue: In a world where a piano is a weapon, not  a musical instrument, on what does Scott Joplin play "The Maple Leaf Rag"?

00:00:52:057000.Speaker: Leonard
00:00:52:057000.Dialogue: What the hell are you guys playing?

00:00:55:577000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:00:55:577000.Dialogue: It's a game we invented. It's called Counterfactuals.

00:00:59:531000.Speaker: Amy
00:00:59:531000.Dialogue: We postulate an alternate world that differs from ours in one key aspect and then pose questions to each other.

00:01:04:419000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:01:04:419000.Dialogue: It's fun for ages eight to 80. Join us.

00:01:07:706000.Speaker: Leonard
00:01:07:706000.Dialogue: All right. I like a good brainteaser. Give it a whirl.

00:01:12:260000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:01:12:260000.Dialogue: You're in luck; this is an easy one. In a world where mankind is ruled by a giant intelligent beaver, what food is no longer consumed?

00:01:21:886000.Speaker: Leonard
00:01:21:886000.Dialogue: Uh... a BLT where the B stands for beaver? I don't know.

00:01:28:009000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:01:28:009000.Dialogue: Leonard, be serious. We're playing a game here.

00:01:32:814000.Speaker: Leonard
00:01:32:814000.Dialogue: I can figure this out. Let's see. Um, well, beavers eat tree bark. The only tree bark I know that humans consume is cinnamon. So, I'll say cinnamon.

00:01:42:741000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:01:42:741000.Dialogue: Incorrect. Obviously, the answer is cheese Danish.

00:01:48:613000.Speaker: Amy
00:01:48:613000.Dialogue: In a world ruled by a giant beaver, mankind builds many dams to please the beaver overlord. The low-lying city of Copenhagen is flooded. Thousands die. Devastated, the Danes never invent their namesake pastry.

00:02:07:866000.Speaker: Leonard
00:02:07:866000.Dialogue: This is ridiculous. You're just making stuff up.

00:02:11:269000.Speaker: Amy
00:02:11:269000.Dialogue: Is he always like this when he loses?

00:02:13:588000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:02:13:588000.Dialogue: Oh, yes. You should've been here for the great Jenga tantrum of 2008.

00:02:20:478000.Speaker: Leonard
00:02:20:478000.Dialogue: You bumped the table and you know it.

00:02:26:334000.Speaker: Amy
00:02:26:334000.Dialogue: Perhaps it would be kinder to play a game more suited to his abilities. We'll close our eyes and count to ten while you hide.

00:02:37:429000.Speaker: Amy
00:02:37:429000.Dialogue: Very good, Leonard. But next time, don't tell us where you're hiding.

00:03:08:576000.Speaker: Leonard
00:03:08:576000.Dialogue: Did you guys see the paper in <i>The American Physics on supersolids? It's pretty interesting. This guy's working from a hypothesis where...

00:03:20:481000.Speaker: Howard
00:03:20:481000.Dialogue: On the potty? What are you, five?

00:03:22:583000.Speaker: Raj
00:03:22:583000.Dialogue: It's a potty. What do you call it?

00:03:25:586000.Speaker: Raj
00:03:25:586000.Dialogue: That's a little vulgar for the dinner table, don't you think?

00:03:29:824000.Speaker: Raj
00:03:29:824000.Dialogue: Potty is innocent. Potty is adorable.

00:03:31:943000.Speaker: Howard
00:03:31:943000.Dialogue: What do you do in the potty, wee-wee?

00:03:34:712000.Speaker: Raj
00:03:34:712000.Dialogue: If I don't have to boom-boom.

00:03:38:049000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:03:38:049000.Dialogue: Greetings. You all remember Amy Farrah Fowler.

00:03:44:839000.Speaker: Amy
00:03:44:839000.Dialogue: I must take responsibility. I had to stop for feminine hygiene supplies.

00:03:48:726000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:03:48:726000.Dialogue: I believe she's experiencing her menses.

00:03:51:846000.Speaker: Amy
00:03:51:846000.Dialogue: Actually, I'm not. In order to avoid surprises, I wear them all the time.

00:03:57:068000.Speaker: Howard
00:03:57:068000.Dialogue: Toilet's sounding pretty good now, huh?

00:04:04:242000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:04:04:242000.Dialogue: A juvenile amalgamation of our names. Sheldon, Amy-- Shamy.

00:04:09:947000.Speaker: Amy
00:04:09:947000.Dialogue: Oh. I don't like that. Don't do that.

00:04:16:420000.Speaker: Amy
00:04:16:420000.Dialogue: Well, just recently, I learned that you refer to us as Shamy, and I don't like that.

00:04:20:241000.Speaker: Penny
00:04:20:241000.Dialogue: I got it. But what I was going for was, you know, how's your life?

00:04:24:862000.Speaker: Amy
00:04:24:862000.Dialogue: Like everybody else's. Subject to entropy, decay and eventual death.

00:04:31:185000.Speaker: Amy
00:04:31:185000.Dialogue: Thank you for asking. Why is she not taking our order?

00:04:34:272000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:04:34:272000.Dialogue: I should've warned you, one has to navigate a labyrinth of social nonsense before one can be fed here.

00:04:40:611000.Speaker: Amy
00:04:40:611000.Dialogue: Really? I assumed an establishment called the Cheesecake Factory would function more efficiently.

00:04:46:450000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:04:46:450000.Dialogue: It's how they lure you in. I believe it's called " bait and switch."

00:04:50:905000.Speaker: Penny
00:04:50:905000.Dialogue: Okay, I'm just gonna walk away, cause... I don't want to be here.

00:04:58:829000.Speaker: Leonard
00:04:58:829000.Dialogue: So, this is nice. First time we've all gotten together to eat.

00:05:07:288000.Speaker: Leonard
00:05:07:288000.Dialogue: Okay, that's all I got. Howard, you're up.

00:05:11:309000.Speaker: Howard
00:05:11:309000.Dialogue: Um... tell us about your work, Amy.

00:05:14:812000.Speaker: Amy
00:05:14:812000.Dialogue: I doubt you'd understand. Sheldon tells me you only have a master's degree.

00:05:21:068000.Speaker: Howard
00:05:21:068000.Dialogue: Raj, do you have any questions for Amy?

00:05:26:473000.Speaker: Amy
00:05:26:473000.Dialogue: I'm curious as to why we're not eating alone.

00:05:30:061000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:05:30:061000.Dialogue: They can't function without me. I'm the social glue that holds this little group together. You're welcome.

00:05:40:838000.Speaker: Leonard
00:05:40:838000.Dialogue: Listen, can I talk to you about your girlfriend?

00:05:43:708000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:05:43:708000.Dialogue: She's not my girlfriend. She's a girl and she's my friend, but there's no touching or unsanitary exchange of saliva.

00:05:54:051000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:05:54:051000.Dialogue: Although, for the record, on one occasion, she licked her thumb to remove raspberry jelly from the corner of my mouth. It's an action we both regret to this day.

00:06:02:943000.Speaker: Leonard
00:06:02:943000.Dialogue: Uh-huh. Anyway, I'm not sure she's the best fit for our little-- how should we call it-- rebel alliance.

00:06:10:017000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:06:10:017000.Dialogue: Oh, I never identified with the rebel alliance. Despite their tendency to build Death Stars, I've always been more of an empire man.

00:06:21:028000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:06:21:028000.Dialogue: I know what your point is. You're intimidated by Amy's intellect. To that I say, buck up.

00:06:26:751000.Speaker: Leonard
00:06:26:751000.Dialogue: Okay, let me just get right to it. Amy is judgmental, sanctimonious and frankly... just obnoxious.

00:06:37:428000.Speaker: Leonard
00:06:37:428000.Dialogue: So we already have you for all that.

00:06:41:182000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:06:41:182000.Dialogue: Are you suggesting I terminate my relationship with Amy?

00:06:44:402000.Speaker: Leonard
00:06:44:402000.Dialogue: No, no, of course not. Just have your relationship someplace else.

00:06:48:906000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:06:48:906000.Dialogue: May I point out that for eight long months, I suffered in silence as your female companion filled our apartment with her off-key country music caterwauling, the unappetizing spectacle of her grinding a pumice stone against her calloused feet in our living room, and night after night of uninformative TV documentaries about the Jersey Shore.

00:07:20:921000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:07:20:921000.Dialogue: And I'd thank you to do the same.

00:07:30:815000.Speaker: Raj
00:07:30:815000.Dialogue: Ah. Nothing makes beer taste better than cool clear Rocky Mountain spring water. Where are the Rocky Mountains, anyway?

00:07:44:011000.Speaker: Raj
00:07:44:011000.Dialogue: Really? I thought they were out West someplace.

00:07:46:464000.Speaker: Howard
00:07:46:464000.Dialogue: Think about it, Raj. Where did the movie Rocky take place?

00:07:50:985000.Speaker: Raj
00:07:50:985000.Dialogue: Philadelphia. Okay, now I get it.

00:07:56:891000.Speaker: Penny
00:07:56:891000.Dialogue: So this is the plan? From now on, we're just gonna hide out in here to avoid the Shamy?

00:08:02:229000.Speaker: Raj
00:08:02:229000.Dialogue: I'm very comfortable here. Penny, dear, why don't you shoot another silver bullet my way?

00:08:10:404000.Speaker: Raj
00:08:10:404000.Dialogue: Ooh, somebody's been taking bitchy pills.

00:08:13:657000.Speaker: Penny
00:08:13:657000.Dialogue: God, he's an ass when he drinks.

00:08:17:311000.Speaker: Howard
00:08:17:311000.Dialogue: Oh, he's an ass when he doesn't. You just don't hear it.

00:08:20:865000.Speaker: Leonard
00:08:20:865000.Dialogue: Think we need to start entertaining the possibility that the Shamy could go on for years.

00:08:25:669000.Speaker: Raj
00:08:25:669000.Dialogue: Well, if that's the case, Penny will have to get satellite TV and maybe once a week run a vacuum  through this place.

00:08:35:179000.Speaker: Penny
00:08:35:179000.Dialogue: I thought you were going to talk to Sheldon.

00:08:38:999000.Speaker: Leonard
00:08:38:999000.Dialogue: Well, he pointed out that he kinda sorta had to... put up with you.

00:09:13:367000.Speaker: Howard
00:09:13:367000.Dialogue: And someday, when you have varicose veins, I'll show you how to massage them.

00:09:24:895000.Speaker: Leonard
00:09:24:895000.Dialogue: I assume by "never again, you mean never again will you drink all of Penny's beer,then run down to the gas station for a couple of 40s, a box of Slim Jims and the latest issue of Bombay Badonkadonks.

00:09:40:593000.Speaker: Howard
00:09:40:593000.Dialogue: The highlight of the evening was when you showed us your Bollywood break dancing skills.

00:10:05:752000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:10:05:752000.Dialogue: I brought Amy here to show her some of the work I'm doing.

00:10:09:223000.Speaker: Amy
00:10:09:223000.Dialogue: It's very impressive, for theoretical work.

00:10:13:394000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:10:13:394000.Dialogue: Do I detect a hint of condescension?

00:10:15:763000.Speaker: Amy
00:10:15:763000.Dialogue: I'm sorry, was I being too subtle?

00:10:19:233000.Speaker: Amy
00:10:19:233000.Dialogue: I meant compared to the real-world applications of neurobiology, theoretical physics is-- what's the word I'm looking for?-- hmm, cute.

00:10:27:575000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:10:27:575000.Dialogue: Are you suggesting the work of a neurobiologist like Babinski could ever rise to the significance of a physicist like Clarke-Maxwell or Dirac?

00:10:38:052000.Speaker: Amy
00:10:38:052000.Dialogue: I'm stating it outright. Babinski eats Dirac for breakfast and defecates Clarke-Maxwell.

00:10:50:481000.Speaker: Amy
00:10:50:481000.Dialogue: Absolutely not. My colleagues and I are mapping the neurological substrates that subserve global information processing, which is required for all cognitive reasoning, including scientific inquiry, making my research ipso facto prior in the ordo cognoscendi. That means it's better than his research, and by extension, of course, yours.

00:11:10:200000.Speaker: Leonard
00:11:10:200000.Dialogue: I'm sorry, I'm-I'm still trying to work on the defecating Clark Maxwell, so...

00:11:17:841000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:11:17:841000.Dialogue: Excuse me, but a grand unified theory, insofar as it explains everything, will ipso facto explain neurobiology.

00:11:27:017000.Speaker: Amy
00:11:27:017000.Dialogue: Yes, but if I'm successful, I will be able to map and reproduce your thought processes in deriving a grand unified theory, and therefore, subsume your conclusions under my paradigm.

00:11:35:893000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:11:35:893000.Dialogue: That's the rankest psychologism, and was conclusively revealed as hogwash by Gottlob Frege in the 1890s!

00:11:43:968000.Speaker: Amy
00:11:43:968000.Dialogue: We appear to have reached an impasse.

00:11:47:071000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:11:47:071000.Dialogue: I agree. I move our relationship terminate immediately.

00:11:58:215000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:11:58:215000.Dialogue: ...the motion carries. Good day, Amy Farrah Fowler.

00:12:08:375000.Speaker: Howard
00:12:08:375000.Dialogue: Women, huh? Can't live with them, can't successfully refute their hypotheses.

00:12:26:759000.Speaker: Penny
00:12:26:759000.Dialogue: I hear you broke up with Amy.

00:12:29:395000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:12:29:395000.Dialogue: A breakup would imply she was my girlfriend. She was a girl who was my friend who is now a girl who is not my friend.

00:12:38:871000.Speaker: Penny
00:12:38:871000.Dialogue: Wow. That's like the worst country song ever.

00:12:51:450000.Speaker: Penny
00:12:51:450000.Dialogue: Well, breakups-- or whatever the hell this is-- can be tough.

00:12:56:672000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:12:56:672000.Dialogue: Penny, I assure you, I'm fine. My relationship with Amy was purely intellectual, There were no emotional bonds, the severing of which would cause me any discomfort. The relationship simply outlived its utility, and I'm continuing on with my life as before.

00:13:14:156000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:13:14:156000.Dialogue: Now, if you'll excuse me, I'm off to buy a pussycat.

00:13:20:245000.Speaker: Leonard
00:13:20:245000.Dialogue: I gotta tell you guys, I'm a little worried about Sheldon.

00:13:23:449000.Speaker: Howard
00:13:23:449000.Dialogue: We're all a little worried about Sheldon.

00:13:26:285000.Speaker: Leonard
00:13:26:285000.Dialogue: No, I mean since the Shamy hit a reef.

00:13:29:321000.Speaker: Howard
00:13:29:321000.Dialogue: Oh, I thought you were just making a generalization: You know, someday setting off a low-yield nuclear device because the cafeteria ran out of lime Jell-O.

00:13:47:222000.Speaker: Leonard
00:13:47:222000.Dialogue: I think Sheldon really misses Amy.

00:13:49:691000.Speaker: Howard
00:13:49:691000.Dialogue: You should lend him your copy of Bombay Badonkadonks.

00:13:53:962000.Speaker: Leonard
00:13:53:962000.Dialogue: He got a cat to keep him company.

00:13:57:149000.Speaker: Leonard
00:13:57:149000.Dialogue: He takes it everywhere: to bed, to the bathroom.

00:14:00:252000.Speaker: Raj
00:14:00:252000.Dialogue: He takes the kitty to the potty?

00:14:02:204000.Speaker: Howard
00:14:02:204000.Dialogue: I thought we discussed the P-word.

00:14:04:823000.Speaker: Raj
00:14:04:823000.Dialogue: Don't try to change me, dude. I am what I am.

00:14:11:696000.Speaker: Howard
00:14:11:696000.Dialogue: Hey. Aren't you going to introduce us to your little friend?

00:14:15:417000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:14:15:417000.Dialogue: My apologies. Raj, Howard, I'd like you to meet Dr. Robert Oppenheimer.

00:14:24:927000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:14:24:927000.Dialogue: Now, if you'll excuse me, the father of the atomic bomb wants a saucer of milk.

00:14:31:567000.Speaker: Howard
00:14:31:567000.Dialogue: Okay, I get it. We're worried about Sheldon.

00:14:45:280000.Speaker: Leonard
00:14:45:280000.Dialogue: So you decided to get the whole Manhattan Project?

00:15:10:022000.Speaker: Leonard
00:15:10:022000.Dialogue: Cats, Sheldon. You're clearly upset about Amy being gone, and you're trying to replace her with a bunch of cats.

00:15:17:946000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:15:17:946000.Dialogue: A group of cats is a clowder. Or a glaring.

00:15:22:367000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:15:22:367000.Dialogue: It's the kind of thing you ought to know now that we have one.

00:15:25:737000.Speaker: Leonard
00:15:25:737000.Dialogue: Terrific. My point is, you need to face up to what you're feeling with this breakup.

00:15:30:959000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:15:30:959000.Dialogue: It wasn't a breakup. A breakup would imply that Amy was my girlfriend.

00:15:34:112000.Speaker: Leonard
00:15:34:112000.Dialogue: Okay, I got it, I got it; she's not your girlfriend. Now listen to me. I know about loneliness. I know about trying to replace someone with other stuff. When I broke up with Penny, I got back into my cello, I built a bunch of model rockets, I got those weightlifting gloves and that five-pound dumbbell.

00:15:53:448000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:15:53:448000.Dialogue: You didn't break up, she dumped you.

00:15:56:818000.Speaker: Leonard
00:15:56:818000.Dialogue: She didn't dump me. It was mutual!

00:16:00:155000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:16:00:155000.Dialogue: I was there. She dumped you.

00:16:01:823000.Speaker: Leonard
00:16:01:823000.Dialogue: Okay, fine. Live with cats. Be like my Aunt Nancy. She had dozens of them. And do you know what happened after she died? They ate her.

00:16:09:615000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:16:09:615000.Dialogue: You don't have to sell me on cats, Leonard. I'm already a fan.

00:16:17:923000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:16:17:923000.Dialogue: All right, fellas, who's in the mood for Fancy Feast? Well, that's not fancy at all.

00:16:29:935000.Speaker: Leonard
00:16:29:935000.Dialogue: Hi, Mrs. Cooper. Thanks for coming.

00:16:33:772000.Speaker: Mrs Cooper
00:16:33:772000.Dialogue: Now, when you said on the phone he broke up with a girl, you meant an actual girl, not something you kids whipped up in a lab?

00:16:45:150000.Speaker: Leonard
00:16:45:150000.Dialogue: No, no, it's not like that. It's, uh... I don't know what it's like. But there is something I should prepare you for.

00:16:52:908000.Speaker: Mrs Cooper
00:16:52:908000.Dialogue: Oh, relax, Leonard, I have raised that boy. I've seen him at his best, I've seen him at his worst. There's nothing he can do that'll surprise me.

00:17:15:180000.Speaker: Mrs Cooper
00:17:15:180000.Dialogue: My, my, that's a powerful smell.

00:17:19:017000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:17:19:017000.Dialogue: I'd like you to meet Oppenheimer, Frisch, Panofsky, Feynman, Weisskopf...

00:17:24:740000.Speaker: Mrs Cooper
00:17:24:740000.Dialogue: Yeah, I get it. You got a lot of cats and you gave 'em cute Jewish names.

00:17:31:580000.Speaker: Mrs Cooper
00:17:31:580000.Dialogue: Leonard called. And he said that you were pining for a young lady.

00:17:36:067000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:17:36:067000.Dialogue: Oh, that's preposterous. I'm not pining over anyone.

00:17:39:905000.Speaker: Mrs Cooper
00:17:39:905000.Dialogue: Oh, lambchop, we can quibble what to call it, but I think we can both agree it's creepy.

00:17:46:578000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:17:46:578000.Dialogue: I do not agree. Cats make wonderful companions. They don't argue or question my intellectual authority, and this little guy here, I think you'll find to be quite zazzy.

00:18:01:777000.Speaker: Mrs Cooper
00:18:01:777000.Dialogue: You should have called sooner. Shelly! Dinner's ready!

00:18:19:127000.Speaker: Amy
00:18:19:127000.Dialogue: Your mother thinks you might be losing your mind over me. As a neurobiologist, I was curious.

00:18:24:783000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:18:24:783000.Dialogue: Well, rest assured, I am in full possession of my faculties.

00:18:31:590000.Speaker: Mrs Cooper
00:18:31:590000.Dialogue: Oh, God bless you, dear. Sheldon, sit down. Let's talk.

00:18:37:262000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:18:37:262000.Dialogue: All right, but you're not fooling me. Whenever you say we have to talk, it means you want me to listen.

00:18:45:320000.Speaker: Mrs Cooper
00:18:45:320000.Dialogue: Now, the reason I called Amy over was to find out what type of person she is. And after chatting a bit, I have to say that while she is a perfectly unique young woman, you two are definitely not suited for each other.

00:19:01:019000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:19:01:019000.Dialogue: That's a peculiar conclusion. By any standard, Amy is more similar to me than anyone I've ever met.

00:19:07:592000.Speaker: Mrs Cooper
00:19:07:592000.Dialogue: Oh, I'm sorry, Shelly, I can't see it.

00:19:10:395000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:19:10:395000.Dialogue: Well, whether you see it or not is irrelevant. I can't see subatomic particles, but nevertheless, they're there.

00:19:22:541000.Speaker: Mrs Cooper
00:19:22:541000.Dialogue: Well, putting aside the pig Latin, it's a good thing that you two decided to end the relationship so I didn't have to end it for you.

00:19:33:602000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:19:33:602000.Dialogue: Amy, after consideration, I believe we may have acted rashly. I propose we resume our relationship and attempt to resolve our differences.

00:19:41:710000.Speaker: Amy
00:19:41:710000.Dialogue: I'll agree to that only if you'll stipulate that 80% of our difficulties were caused by you.

00:19:47:549000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:19:47:549000.Dialogue: Done. You understand that moving forward, we deal with the fact that my mother does not approve of you?

00:19:54:573000.Speaker: Amy
00:19:54:573000.Dialogue: I do. I find being cast in the role of bad girl oddly titillating.

00:20:01:880000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:20:01:880000.Dialogue: Would you like to see my cats?

00:20:03:648000.Speaker: Amy
00:20:03:648000.Dialogue: I would. I love cats. They're the epitome of indifference.

00:20:07:102000.Speaker: Sheldon
00:20:07:102000.Dialogue: Ah, then you may find Zazzles a little cloying.

00:20:11:990000.Speaker: Leonard
00:20:11:990000.Dialogue: I saw what you did there.

00:20:13:775000.Speaker: Mrs Cooper
00:20:13:775000.Dialogue: He thinks he's such a smarty pants. He's no different from any man. You tell 'em not to do something, that's all they want to do. If I hadn't told my brother Stumpy not to clear out the wood chipper by hand, we'd still be calling him Edward.

00:20:27:255000.Scene: Outside. Sheldon is sitting at a table with a sign reading “Cats $20”)
00:20:27:255000.Speaker: Mrs Cooper
00:20:27:255000.Dialogue: Now, don't you move. I'll bring over all the food.

00:20:30:008000.Scene: Outside. Sheldon is sitting at a table with a sign reading “Cats $20”)
00:20:30:008000.Speaker: Leonard
00:20:30:008000.Dialogue: No, no, no, I can do it.
